## Optimal Solution (DP)

### Core Idea

```
State:
  up[v]   = number of valid zigzag sequences
            ending at value v
            where LAST move was UP (v > prev)

  down[v] = number of valid zigzag sequences
            ending at value v
            where LAST move was DOWN (v < prev)

Transition:
  new_up[v]   = sum of down[0..v-1]   ← previous was DOWN, now go UP
  new_down[v] = sum of up[v+1..m-1]   ← previous was UP,  now go DOWN

Optimization:
  Use prefix sums to make each transition O(m) instead of O(m²)
```

### Code

```python
def zigzag_optimal(n, l, r):
    """
    Dynamic Programming with Prefix Sums
    Time:  O(n × m)   where m = r - l + 1
    Space: O(m)
    """
    m = r - l + 1   # number of available values

    # ─── Base Case: length = 1 ────────────────────────────────────────────
    # Single element: no moves yet
    # Treat as both up=0 and down=0 to bootstrap length-2
    
    # ─── Base Case: length = 2 ────────────────────────────────────────────
    # up[i]   = i         (i values smaller than value[i] exist)
    # down[i] = m-1-i     (m-1-i values larger than value[i] exist)
    
    up   = [i       for i in range(m)]   # [0, 1, 2, ..., m-1]
    down = [m-1-i   for i in range(m)]   # [m-1, m-2, ..., 0]

    if n == 1:
        return m   # each single value is trivially zigzag

    if n == 2:
        return sum(up) + sum(down)

    # ─── Fill DP for length 3 → n ─────────────────────────────────────────
    for length in range(3, n + 1):

        # ── Build prefix arrays ───────────────────────────────────────────
        pref_up   = [0] * m
        pref_down = [0] * m

        pref_up[0]   = up[0]
        pref_down[0] = down[0]

        for i in range(1, m):
            pref_up[i]   = pref_up[i-1]   + up[i]
            pref_down[i] = pref_down[i-1] + down[i]

        total_up   = pref_up[-1]    # sum of all up   values
        total_down = pref_down[-1]  # sum of all down values

        # ── Compute new states ────────────────────────────────────────────
        new_up   = [0] * m
        new_down = [0] * m

        for v in range(m):
            # new_up[v]: last move UP to v
            #   need DOWN sequence ending at value < v
            #   = pref_down[v-1]
            new_up[v] = pref_down[v-1] if v > 0 else 0

            # new_down[v]: last move DOWN to v
            #   need UP sequence ending at value > v
            #   = total_up - pref_up[v]
            new_down[v] = total_up - pref_up[v]

        up   = new_up
        down = new_down

    return sum(up) + sum(down)


# ─── Run ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
print(zigzag_optimal(3, 1, 3))   # → 10
```

